## Verdict: CONCERN

### 1. [medium] Timeout breaks strict embed serialization after the watchdog fires
Refs: `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3446-3457`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3490-3502`

`embed_serialize` only covers the worker’s wait on `recv_timeout`, not the lifetime of the underlying `embedder.embed()` call. When a call times out, the worker drops the mutex and retries, but the detached embed thread keeps running. That means later retries or jobs can re-enter the shared embedder concurrently with the abandoned call, so the PR-9 “one embed at a time” fix stops being true on the timeout path. Given the pre-flight result, this looks like a robustness/perf risk rather than an immediate writer/cursor correctness break, but it is the main remaining hole in the serialization + watchdog composition.

<details>
<summary>What passed on inspection</summary>

The commit path still stays outside the new embed mutex. `run_projection_job` acquires `embed_serialize` only around `embed_with_watchdog`, and commit remains later in `run_projection_jobs` via `commit_projection_outcomes`, under the existing separate `commit_gate` (`src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3467-3510`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3392-3401`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3822-3832`).

Single-writer and projection-cursor freshness contracts look preserved on inspection. The new logic does not move commit/cursor advancement, and worker panic cleanup still routes through the existing batch-level `catch_unwind` and state decrement path (`src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3347-3369`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3980-3989`).

Panic transparency is implemented correctly: watchdog-thread panics are caught and resumed on the worker thread, so the existing `ProjectionPanic` machinery remains in force (`src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3446-3457`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3353-3359`).

The direct mechanism tests are honest about what they assert. `pr9_embed_serialization.rs` really checks `max_in_flight == 1`, and `pr9_embed_watchdog.rs` covers drain return, terminal failure/no stored vector, subsequent-write recovery, and a non-timeout slow case (`src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/pr9_embed_serialization.rs:84-118`, `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/pr9_embed_watchdog.rs:145-244`).
</details>

